My heart goes out to the family and friends  of the man who died in an avalanche in Cooke city the other day. 

We as a community need to change these tragic moments. Because they are avoidable, it’s not crazy to ask this. 

Everyone needs a Transceiver, and more importantly the knowledge of how to use it! Probe and shovel is next and practice to know how to be effective. 

Avoidance would be the best strategy however we all make mistakes. 

But even above all else, please ride one at a time in avalanche terrain!!! And don’t park in the run out!!!!!! 

Read the avalanche advisory where ever possible, or avoid suspect slopes if you don’t have the information about that snowpack!

We ride in hazardous terrain and everyone should have some basic training to support this, please help change the culture so we can help eachother!

Down here in the Stanislaus forest on Hwy 4 teaching a @savycenter level 1 Avy course.
The amount t of terrain that the USFS unlawfully closed is alarming. They are trying to keep us out of public lands, push us out of communities, and destroy us. 
They have made these closures on fake data, and incomplete data. The impact that OSV has on the forest is far less in an entire season than even one Saturdays traffic to any Ski resort in the sierra. 

Please please please go help our community and the @sierrasnowmobilefoundation in fighting the injustice that continues to occur brought on by the USFS, and Winter wild lands, snow lands network, Tahoe backcountry alliance, Patagonia, north face, and the list goes on. 
If we don’t fight to keep our public lands open then they will close them down to OSV use and only allow the elites to be granted access. 

Sierra snowmobile foundation is giving away a snowmobile for your donations so get on it! I think it’s the last day to get tix. 

These rulings in Cali will spread to the rest of the western US, so yes it impacts all of us!!! 

#help #injustice #ssf #publiclands #fightforyourright #publicaccess #bullshit

What avalanche airbag do I wear? 

This year I’m running the @highmarkbysnowpulse Pro P.A.S. Pack. It’s 22 liters of storage designed for motorized use. Which means the pull handle is on the right shoulder and it’s built tuff enough to withstand some serious abuse. It has a dedicated probe sleeve inside the pack, and external shovel carry system. The airbag is  @mammut_swiss1862 technology which is compressed air mechanical system. It has two external pockets. On the inside it has a water bladder holder (which I keep my snow science saw in) a radio zipper pocket along with routing through the shoulder strap for the mic to feed through. And two internal pockets. Here is a list of all the stuff I carry in my pack:
@mammutna Shovel
@mammutna 320mm Probe
Snow science kit (crystal card, loop, field book, ect cord, extendable rulers, popsicle sticks, thermometers…)
@mountainlabgear First aid kit with Sam splint 
Extra pair of @fxrracing gloves
Extra @fxrracing goggles
In- reach satellite device
@mountainlabgear 2way radio
@mountainlabgear 1800 lumen helmet light 
@mountainlabgear multi tool
GoPro 360
3 snack bars
1 lighter
Enough Trail money

Sounds heavy, but it’s not too bad, it fits great, and snugs up tight.

I make sure to test my airbag a minimum of once a season, and check to make sure the canister is full and good to go every week. 
I hope to never have to deploy this airbag, but if I need to i trust it will work.
However, my strategy to not get buried is to avoid avalanches and my airbag is a last resort in hopes it will help my survival. I also make sure I ride with partners who know how to perform a correct rescue, and practice with their rescue gear. 

#highmarkbysnowpulse #airbag #avalancheeducation #avyed #getsmart #letsride #backpack #snowmobile #fun #safety #wheelietime

What should I look for in an avalanche report?

Find out when the avalanche center closest to your riding area publishes their avalanche report.  Then make it a habit to check the report every day.  This will give you practice for analyzing the report consistently, but also make you more aware of the components provided in the report.

If there is something you are unsure of in the report, be sure to utilize the links provided to get additional information to expand your knowledge.

Here are some features to be aware of in the report regarding avalanche problems:

1.  Type
2.  Location
3.  Likelihood
4.  Size

I drew an archery mule deer tag in Nevada this season. Went out two nights before opening day. My good friend @chloestrent joined me and we hiked in 4.7 miles with 2,800 feet elevation gain. 

From there we saw a group of 12 bachelors across the valley. The next day we watched them…. Saw 6 other hunters, but nobody was going after this group. So what did we do the next sunrise? Yup….. hiked another 3.3 miles across this valley to the base of the mtn they were on. Unloaded our camping gear and I went on a 6 hour stalk with another 800ft elevation gain. 

Thunderstorms moved in and the thunder and rain provided a great opportunity, (it also drenched our camping gear at the base of the mtn) after crawling around some rock ledges, and trying to find a way in, I got out in the sage on an open face while this group started to move my way…. 
Of course the wind shifted, they got my scent once they were within 50 yards, but could not see me sitting right there in the open. I was having trouble seeing through the water drops on my range finder, but at the last moment before they all took off I had one who stopped long enough at 38 yards for me to take the shot. I made the kill at 6pm. (Swipe right to see) 

Trent and I field dressed it and then proceeded to hike 4.3 miles down a ravine bush wacking all night to the road. 110 pound pack in the dark, with no trail and only our maps and satellite imagery….. (if your gonna be dumb you better be tuff) ….many moments that night I had to tell myself to just keep going. It’s truly amazing what we are capable of, and even though I’m still sore 4 days later…. I feel amazing. Grateful, thankful, and I am proud to provide the best protein and nourishment for my family. This deer that we will consume did not make it easy, and through hard work and determination we honor its being. 🙏 

Archery mule deer season was only a 3 day trip for me this year. But memory’s for a lifetime.

Why should you get avalanche training?

It is important for your to attend an awareness talk or something to get your head in the game.  You want to make sure you are set up for success this season and that you are thinking about the dangers out there.  You want to get the right education and formal training so you can get the experience on the snow coupled with a professional.  This training will help you understand the snowpack, weak layers, the terrain, group management, how and when to play on the right slopes so you can have a great time.

Avalanche education used to be looked at as schooling inside.  Well, these days the training has been revised to be fun, exciting, out in the field, hands in the snow, riding awesome terrain, and having a great time.

Be sure to check out the avalanche awareness talk schedule and avalanche training providers that are available on our website.  Get signed up today to ensure you are prepared for your next backcountry excursion.

What do you do when you get a transciever signal?

Once you pick up a signal, inform the rest of your searching group.  Continue in your signal search pattern until you have a consistent signal.  Communicate that you have a signal.  Then slow your pace and keep the light or arrow in the center.  Move forward to get the numbers on the display to get smaller.  Hold your transceiver flat and pivot it until you get the direction of the strongest signal.  Once oriented, follow it until you get to the burial site.  Move slower and more precisely below 20 meters.  Below 10 meters, look behind you where you came from and double check your center arrow.  Record your tranjectory by putting your helmet on the snow facing the direction you are going.

Well not surprised on the amount of activity right now, and there might not be a lot of signs of instability as you ride, but you can remote trigger avalanches right now. This was the first of two that we remotely triggered today. We were intentionally staying off of slopes over 30 degrees, however being near them right now even if you’re not in the run out or start zone, you can still trigger them. There are a lot of reports on the @savycenter observations page from today already of many remotely triggered avalanches in the region. Things are spicey and breaking bigger and father than you might expect. Staying out of and off of avalanche terrain is the way to ride right now. Time and weather is the only way we will see these layers fix them selves. Heads up ball game rt now folks!
